{"id":1185,"date":"2021-02-16T21:51:28","date_gmt":"2021-02-16T16:21:28","guid":{"rendered":"http:\/\/localhost?page_id=1185"},"modified":"2023-11-06T23:20:20","modified_gmt":"2023-11-06T17:50:20","slug":"di","status":"publish","type":"page","link":"http:\/\/localhost\/?page_id=1185","title":{"rendered":"Digital Art"},"content":{"rendered":"\n<div class=\"wp-block-buttons is-layout-flex wp-block-buttons-is-layout-flex\">\n<div class=\"wp-block-button has-custom-width wp-block-button__width-100 has-custom-font-size is-style-outline has-small-font-size\"><a class=\"wp-block-button__link has-background-color has-foreground-background-color has-text-color has-background has-link-color wp-element-button\" href=\"http:\/\/localhost\/\" style=\"border-radius:100px;padding-top:var(--wp--preset--spacing--30);padding-bottom:var(--wp--preset--spacing--30)\">Homepage<\/a><\/div>\n<\/div>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"has-text-align-center\">For digital arts, I start on paper. Making rough or taking a finished sketch. Scan them into computer. Open scans in Photoshop. Begin adding layers. Add effects to sketches. Experiment with backgrounds, foregrounds. Place objects in scenes. Add artifacts and surroundings. Create environments around sketches. Adjust lighting, shadows, glare, reflections. Spend time colorizing sketches. Correct any distortion from scans. Improve contrasts between layers. All work done manually pixel by pixel. I enjoy challenge of doing everything by hand. Find it rewarding to see sketches transform into finished pieces through long process. Here all are downscaled to less than 1000-pixel height and width.<\/p>\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\">\n<figure class=\"aligncenter size-full\"><img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1000\" height=\"678\" src=\"http:\/\/localhost\/wp-content\/uploads\/3-2-1.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-2581\" srcset=\"http:\/\/localhost\/wp-content\/uploads\/3-2-1.jpg 1000w, http:\/\/localhost\/wp-content\/uploads\/3-2-1-300x203.jpg 30